<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>Milosophical Me (tip konsole kde)</title><link>http://milosophical.me/</link><description></description><atom:link href="http://milosophical.me/tags/tip-konsole-kde.xml" type="application/rss+xml" rel="self"></atom:link><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Mon, 01 Jun 2015 22:32:27 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>http://getnikola.com/</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>KDE Konsole's title bar and prompt</title><link>http://milosophical.me/blog/2010/05/07/kde-konsoles-title-bar-and-prompt.html</link><dc:creator>Mike Lockhart</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;I spent the past hour fiddling with Konsole, trying to get it to honor my Bash prompt in the title bar (using the usual ESC char tricks you can find anywhere).  Finally found it:  In the Profile settings, under Tabs, change the tab tiles to %w (or pick "Window title set by Shell" from the drop-down Insert list to the right).&lt;/p&gt;</description><category>hacking</category><category>tip konsole kde</category><guid>http://milosophical.me/blog/2010/05/07/kde-konsoles-title-bar-and-prompt.html</guid><pubDate>Fri, 07 May 2010 13:03:07 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>